    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1972-05-31T09:30:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1972-05-31T09:30:00-05:00" n="264"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d264">
                <head>264. Telegram 6684 From the <gloss type="from">Embassy in India</gloss> to the
                        <gloss type="to">Department of State</gloss>
                    <note n="1" type="source" xml:id="d264fn1">Source: National Archives, <gloss
                            target="#t_RG1">RG</gloss> 59, Central Files 1970–73, <gloss
                            target="#t_AID1">AID</gloss> (<gloss target="#t_US1">US</gloss>) INDIA.
                        Secret; Priority; Nodis. Eyes Only for <persName corresp="#p_HJA1"
                            >Hannah</persName> and <persName corresp="#p_SJJ1">Sisco</persName>.
                        Additional documentation on the further reduction of U.S. economic and
                        technical assistance programs in India can be found ibid.</note>
                    <note n="2" type="summary" xml:id="d264fn2">The question of eliminating the U.S.
                        technical assistance program was considered at “the highest levels,” and it
                        was decided that India would continue to request technical assistance in
                        areas where U.S. technical superiority was obvious.</note>
                </head>
                <dateline>
                    <placeName>New Delhi</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                        when="1972-05-31T14:30:00+00:00">May 31, 1972, 1430Z</date>
                </dateline>
                <list type="subject">
                    <head>Subject:</head>
                    <item>
                        <gloss target="#t_USAID1">USAID</gloss>/India Technical Assistance
                        Program</item>
                </list>
                <list type="references">
                    <head>Ref:</head>
                    <item>New Delhi 6181</item>
                </list>
                <list>
                    <label>1.</label>
                    <item>Mission Director and Evans, Program Division Chief, have had separate
                        meetings with Krishnaswami and <gloss target="#t_DEA1">DEA</gloss> staff
                        during past week.</item>
                    <label>2.</label>
                    <item>Evans was told that elimination of the U.S. technical assitance program
                        had been discussed at “the highest levels”. <gloss target="#t_DEA1"
                            >DEA</gloss> argued that U.S. aid, whether bilateral or through
                        multilateral channels, was of great importance to India, so a compromise was
                        reached whereby the <gloss target="#t_GOI1">GOI</gloss> would continue to
                        request technical assistance in a few selected areas where U.S. superiority
                        was obvious.</item>
                    <label>3.</label>
                    <item>Krishnaswami said to Houston that the <gloss target="#t_GOI1">GOI</gloss>
                        did not like discussing “bits and pieces” of the aid program. They would
                        prefer to talk about an aid program “in its totality”. Therefore, until such
                        time as this might happen, the <gloss target="#t_GOI1">GOI</gloss> will sign
                        no new TA agreements, at least for <gloss target="#t_FY1">FY</gloss> 72 and
                        73. He carefully pointed out that the <gloss target="#t_GOI1">GOI</gloss>
                        would sign proage necessary to continue on-going projects.</item>
                    <label>4.</label>
                    <item>
                        <gloss target="#t_DEA1">DEA</gloss> proposes eliminating the agricultural
                        production and agricultural inputs programs. They plan to take over directly
                        costs involved in Iffco. Within a ceiling of about thirty technicians, they
                        would like to continue agricultural universities development, rice research,
                        soil &amp; water, rural electric coops, science education, and nutritional
                        foods development. Personnel levels in these projects are being
                        negotiated.</item>
                    <pb facs="d264-02" n="2" xml:id="d264-02"/>
                    <label>5.</label>
                    <item>There was consierable discussion about U.S. and Indian support staff.
                        Houston said the numbers would have to be reduced in line with the size of
                        the program. He pointed out that Indian employees would most likely blame
                        the <gloss target="#t_GOI1">GOI</gloss> for what will be substantially
                        number of separations. Krishnaswami seemed quite concerned about the
                        situation.</item>
                    <label>6.</label>
                    <item>The subject of Nepalese participants in India was discussed. Krishnaswami
                        told Houston that “in view of the present uncertainties the <gloss
                            target="#t_GOI1">GOI</gloss> would be unable to approve the program for
                        the current year.” FYI: 164 requests for such training have been held by
                            <gloss target="#t_DEA1">DEA</gloss> for two months 271 Nepalese are in
                        India now and we do not believe they will be affected. End FYI. We are
                        advising USAID/Nepal.</item>
                    <label>7.</label>
                    <item>Trust fund replenishment is a recurrent theme in our discussions. <gloss
                            target="#t_DEA1">DEA</gloss> officials seem paralyzed at the thought of
                        asking Parliament for an appropriation to cover locals costs of the U.S. aid
                        program. <gloss target="#t_PL1">PL</gloss> 480 (!) loan funds they consider
                        to be almost as difficult. We intend to keep pressing <gloss
                            target="#t_DEA1">DEA</gloss> on this subject in view of the imminent
                        depletion of these funds.</item>
                    <label>8.</label>
                    <item>Expect another meeting early next week.</item>
                </list>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_KKB1">Keating</persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
